@Jack | τensora while running miner, should I set the `min_stake_allowed` value instead of using default value?
That’s because the default required min stake is 30k TAO. From my pov it’s better set the min stake to a smaller value (not sure what is the purpose of it, since other subnets usually use 1k)

You can set it to whatever value you like! 

Because of the way the consensus mechanism works in Bittensor though, setting it lower won’t really help you score.

It’s all down to Kappa values and clipping, but in essence currently on the subnet we have a kappa value of 49%, which means this is the amount of weighted stake needed by validators to set your consensus. The UID 0 validator has this on its own, so you actually only “need” to respond to that single validator. 

We actually followed the example of subnet 34 on this, as setting a high default stake, means that tiny validators which are often the validators that relay mine cannot do so on our subnet
So you can set it to any value you like, but we have set it high to limit access on the subnet to only larger more reputable validators which we trust more

async def process_event_data(self, event_data: dict) -> List[Dict]:
        """
        Processes event data across multiple blocks.
        """
        if not isinstance(event_data, dict):
            logger.error(f"Expected event_data to be a dict, got: {type(event_data)}")
            return []
        if not event_data:
            logger.error("No event data provided.")
            return []

        logger.debug(f"Parsing event data from {len(event_data)} blocks.")
        start_time = time.time()

        tasks = []
        for block_key, block_events in event_data.items():
            try:
                bn = int(block_key)
            except ValueError:
                logger.error(f"Block key {block_key} is not convertible to int. Skipping...")
                continue

            if not isinstance(block_events, (list, tuple)):
                logger.error(f"Block {bn} events are not in a tuple or list. Skipping...")
                continue

            tasks.append(self.parse_events(block_events, bn, self.semaphore))

        results = await asyncio.gather(*tasks, return_exceptions=True)

        all_parsed_events = []
        for i, result in enumerate(results):
            if isinstance(result, Exception):
                print(f"Error parsing block {list(event_data.keys())[i]}: {result}")
            else:
                all_parsed_events.extend(result)
